{"key":"post-20000812","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>20000812</id>\n<content>&lt;/font&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;small&quot;&gt;Quote:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;This has been a heated debate for years, most labs store their plates upside down, while most old school myco dudes (aka RR) absolutely disagree with this storage method. &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;post&quot;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;No, most labs do not store petri dishes upside down.&amp;nbsp; In fact, I know of absolutely zero mycology labs which would use such a poor procedure.&amp;nbsp; Local labs which test water samples and the like do so because they only keep the cultures for a few days.&amp;nbsp; If they kept them upside down in the refrigerator for a week, all the moisture would have drained out to the lid.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;To the original poster, condensation is caused by temperature differential.&amp;nbsp; Simply wrap up or otherwise insulate the dishes for storage in an insulated lunch box or similar and always store cultures right side up.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>20001258</next>\n<prev>20000034</prev>\n<first>19996474</first>\n<last>20003456</last>\n<when>1400330130</when>\n<utime>05/17/14 03:35 PM</utime>\n</post>"}